SPillane has firmly re-established himself as an LB1 and should be treated as such for a plus Week 8 matchup against a shaky, yet explosive Atlanta Falcons offense.

Bethune looked the part once again in Week 8, filling in for the injured Fred Warner and finishing the afternoon with four solos and 10 assists. Tatum may be asked to take on an even larger role with Dee Winters banged up, but is an LB2 option regardless. Bethune has registered 10 or more total tackles in all three games he's seen significant action in. Start him with confidence as a top-20 option for a tasty Week 9 matchup against the New York Giants.

Cashman got back on track in Week 8, racking up six solos, five assists, and one tackle for loss. Cashman started slow in his first week back from the hamstring injury, but is an easy LB2 when healthy. Treat him as such for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Detroit Lions. Add and start Blake everywhere.

Carter showed up again in Week 8, totalling five solos, three assists, and one tackle for loss. Carter has tallied five or more solos in all three games since becoming the starter, and makes for a still ascending LB2 option for a tasty Week 9 matchup against the Chicago Bears. Barrett should be rostered universally and starting in all competitive formats. Make it so for Week 9.

Demario was at it again in Week 8, stacking four solos, seven assists, and one forced fumble. The LB6 overall on the season, it is time to start taking the veteran linebacker seriously as a top-15 option, at least until he cools down. Treat him as such for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Landman was excellent in Week 7, reeling off three solos, six assists, 1.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. Landman saw his eight solo streak snapped at two games, and is riding high with three straight spike weeks. Fire him up as a top-15 play for a plus Week 9 matchup against the New Orleans Saints.

Okereke showed up in Week 8, tallying seven solos, one assist, and one sack. Okereke has been a bit of a disappointment for IDP managers and should now be counted as more of an LB3 than LB2 despite the strong performance. Treat him as such despite the plus Week 9 matchup against the San Francisco 49ers.

Elliss was excellent in Week 8, racking up seven solos, five assists, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Elliss has been a peaks and valleys player this season, but has managed more peaks than valleys since Week 3. Tap Elliss as a borderline LB2 option for a plus Week 9 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Devin White was excellent in Week 7, racking up six solos, 10 assists, and one tackle for loss. White has tallied five or more solos in five of his seven games this season, forcing his way back into the LB1 mix. Continue to treat him as a top-15 option as long as he is hot. Start him with confidence for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

Demetrius Knight was excellent in Week 8, racking up six solos, six assists, and one pass defended. The rookie linebacker has been inconsistent, as is to be expected from a rookie, but has still managed to cement himself as a reliable LB3 option. Treat him as such for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Chicago Bears.

Dee was excellent in Week 8, stacking seven solos and four assists before leaving the game with a knee injury. Winters is an easy LB2 play if he is healthy for Week 9, especially with the New York Giants on the schedule.

Eric Wilson was at it again in Week 8, tallying six solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. The veteran linebacker continues to play over Ivan Pace and has been rewarding Brian Flores for his confidence in him. Wilson has recorded four or more solos in four of his last five games, and makes for an excellent LB3 option for what should be a busy night against Jahmyr Gibbs and the Detroit Lions.

Rozeboom was excellent in Week 8, racking up seven solos, five assists, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Rozeboom has been a bit of a boom or bust proposition this season, registering five or more solos in four of his eight contests, while managing three or fewer in the other four. Still, the Panthers linebacker is worth a long look as an LB3 option during the byes, especially with Carolina not having a bye of their own until Week 14. Start Rozeboom as an LB3 with LB2 upside for what projects as a plus Week 9 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Teddye was excellent in Week 8, tallying four solos, two assists, and two tackles for loss. Buchanan has been producing at an LB2 level over his last three contests and can be counted as one for Week 9, thanks to a plus matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Germane Pratt saw his snap share drop again in Week 8, finishing the afternoon with three solos, five assists, and one tackle for loss on 48 percent of the snaps. It is a concern that Pratt is seeing his snaps drop every week, so fantasy managers need to react accordingly and treat him as an 11 v 11 flex option at best until further notice.

Trevin Wallace (LB - CAR) SIT START
Trevin Wallace showed up in Week 8, racking up five solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Trevin hasn't been much more than a bye week filler, managing four or more solos just three times in his eight contests. Also dealing with a shoulder stinger, keep Wallace on rosters, but on benches for Week 9, despite the plus matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Elandon was excellent in Week 7, racking up seven solos, 11 assists, and one tackle for loss. Roberts is back in the starting lineup following the release of Germaine Pratt, as the veteran linebacker was slated to open the season as a starter but lost the job to injury and the resurgence of Devin White. Now with a near everydown role, he can be counted as an LB3 with obvious LB2 upside. Treat him as such for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

Akeem Davis-Gaither 1% SIT START WK9
ADG was excellent in Week 7, racking up four solos, four assists, one forced fumble, and one pass defended. Davis-Gaither has recorded four or more solos in four of his last five games, but it has still been a disappointing season thus far, given the upside he flashed as a spot starter in Cincinnati. Regardless, ADG is a strong LB3 play for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Gary was excellent in Week 8, racking up three solos, one assist, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Rashan currently sits fifth in the league with 7.5 sacks and makes for a strong DL1 candidate for a tasty Week 9 matchup against the Carolina Panthers. Start him with confidence.

Khalil was excellent against the Minnesota Vikings in Week 8, tallying two solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss on 57 percent of the snaps. Mack is up to three sacks in four games, with at least one sack in three of those four. The veteran pass rusher has been playing at a high level when he has been healthy and is a sneaky DL2 option for Week 9, thanks to a saliva-inducing matchup against Cam Ward and the disaster that is the Tennessee Titans. Start Khalil with confidence.

Chamarri was excellent in Week 8, finishing Monday Night Football with five solos and five assists. Conner has had a couple of down weeks this season, but it has been a pretty stable ride with Chamarri overall. He sits as a DB3 in fantasy points due to two truly pitiful outings from a fantasy perspective, but can still be counted as a DB2 option during the byes. Start him with confidence for what should be a busy Sunday afternoon against the Buffalo Bills.

Metellus was excellent in Week 8, racking up three solos, three assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Metellus has dropped to DB3 territory this season but has still been a stable producer for fantasy managers, recording four or more solos in four of his seven contests. Tap him as a high-end DB3 option for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Detroit Lions.

Lake was excellent in Week 7, tallying four solos, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, and two passes defended. Quentin has registered four or more solos in three of his last four games and has been buoyed by peripheral contributions. Fire him up as a DB1 option for a plus Week 9 matchup against the New Orleans Saints.

Chinn was excellent in Week 7, racking up eight solos, four assists, and one forced fumble. Chinn has tallied four or more solos in five of his last six games. Chinn has been a top-15 producer this season and should be treated as one for a tasty Week 9 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

Marcus Jones was at it again in Week 8, tallying five solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, and two passes defended. The DB2 overall since Week 4, Jones has bullied his way into becoming a part of the DB1 conversation. He has simply been too productive to ignore, even in leagues where you only start one or two IDP players. Start Jones everywhere as an IDP1/2 as long as he remains on fire.

Geno Stone showed up in Week 8, racking up seven solos and two assists. Stone has been inconsistent this season, but has still managed to put together five plus fantasy outings, keeping him in the DB3 mix. Treat him as one for a tasty Week 9 matchup against the Chicago Bears.

Harrison Smith was excellent in Week 8, tallying eight solos and one assist. The veteran safety has finally started looking like his old self now that he is drawing closer to full health and needs to be rostered in all competitive leagues. He has recorded 12 solos over the last two weeks, but more importantly, is flying around the field as we expect him to. Tap him as a DB3 with obvious DB2 upside for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Detroit Lions.

Mustapha showed up in Week 7, tallying six solos, six assists, and one tackle for loss. Malik has emerged as one of the starting safeties on the 49ers roster, as he played 100 percent of the snaps in Week 8, while Marques Sigle and Jason Pinnock took a back seat to Ji'Ayir Brown. Malik looks like he has his role solidified, while Brown will need to keep playing well to hold off Sigle, who disappointed, and Pinnock, who was never signed to start in the first place. Tap Malik as a DB3 option for a plus Week 9 matchup against the banged-up New York Giants.

Jaylinn Hawkins showed up in Week 8, racking up four solos, one assist, one interception, and one pass defended on 100 percent of the snaps. Lost in the mix of his injury, Jaylinn has played every snap in each of his last two games and is cemented in the role with Kyle Dugger shipped off to the Steelers. Hawkins started the season hot before Dugger started siphoning snaps, so IDP managers should act accordingly. Tap Jaylinn as a DB3 option for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Atlanta Falcons.

Kam showed up again in Week 8, racking up four solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Riding back-to-back spike weeks and an interception in two of his last three games, Lassiter has forced his way into the DB1 conversation. Treat him as such for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Riley Moss was excellent in Week 8, tallying four solos, two assists, and four passes defended. Moss gets a lot of work as a Broncos corner not named Pat Surtain and has become a fantasy option because of it. He has safety level solo numbers and has more fantasy points than names like Budda Baker, Tyler Nubin, Cole Bishop, Jalen Thompson, and Jaquan Brisker. You will need to live with the inconsistency if you plan on starting him in DB leagues, but Moss has proven time and time again that he belongs in the DB3 conversation. Treat him as a CB1/DB3 option for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Houston Texans.

Quan showed up in a big way on Monday Night Football, exploding with 10 solos and four assists. It was just his third game all season with four or more solos, so IDP managers shouldn't get too excited, but Quan does have the talent to be much better in fantasy than he has been to this point in his young career. For now, continue to treat him as a DB3/bye week filler type with the understanding that he can cement himself as a DB3 option if he can put together another standout performance under the bright lights, this time against Seattle on Sunday night.

Nahshon Wright was excellent in Week 8, racking up six solos and three assists. Despite inconsistent production, Nahshon has parlayed a pair of massive spike weeks into sitting as the DB16 on the season overall and the DB11 in fppg. Wright needs to be rostered and started in all competitive leagues and should be counted as no less than a low-floor DB2 option. Start him with confidence for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals.

IPM showed up in Week 7, tallying eight solos and two assists. This was the second time in his last three games that he has registered four or more solos, which is hopefully a sign he has tuned the IDP corner after managing the feat just once in his previous four contests. IPM is a DB3 option at best, but has an intriguing Week 9 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

Dee Alford was at it again in Week 8, racking up five solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Alford has caught fire, posting two spike weeks in his last three contests, a span in which he has totalled two sacks and a pick. Fire Alford up as a CB2 who can be treated as a CB1 if you find yourself in a pinch. With another strong outing, Dee can move to the CB1 realm. Start Alford as a CB1/DB3 option where needed for a plus Week 9 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Jeremy Reaves showed up in Week 8, racking up six solos, one assist, and two tackles for loss. The Washington safety has been making some waves over the past weeks and has now officially worked his way into every week DB3 consideration instead of being viewed purely as a bye week filler. Reaves has registered three spike weeks (by his standards) in his last four games and should be started where needed with confidence for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Seattle Seahawks on Sunday Night Football.

Trikweze showed up in Week 8, tallying four solos, one interception, and two passes defended on 76 percent of the snaps. Trik has seen north of 75 percent of the snaps in back-to-back games due to multiple injuries at the position, earning his first start in Week 8. If he gets the nod again, he can be viewed as a CB2 option. Those in DB leagues need not apply.

Wiggins was excellent in Week 8, tallying six solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Wiggins is dealing with a groin injury but was listed as full participant on both Tuesday and Wednesday, and has no injury designation heading into Thursday night's contest. Tap Wiggins as a CB2 or bye week filler DB play for a tasty Week 9 matchup against the Miami Dolphins.
